It was pur- chased out of a small annual fund bequeathed by Charles Long‚ Lord Farnborough‚ to be laid out in additions to the Egerton collection, founded by Francis Egerton, duke of Bridgewater3 and the volume became N o. 1461 of the Egerton manuscripts. The chronicle extends from the foundation of the abbey, in the year 1150, to the resig- nation of the eighteenth abbot, william of Scarborough, in the year 1396, occupying 131 leaves, including indexes and a table of the abbots placed at the beginning of the volume. It is followed by a feodary, a rental, and other pieces relating to the monastery, in the same hand.
